<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06026045 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06026045 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; AVIATION; COMPANY; BUY; UK; TRAVEL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  United Airlines came another step closer to taking ownership of routes fromthe United States to London's Heathrow International Airport. The U.S.Bankruptcy Court in New York gave the Chicago-based carrier the green lightFriday to buy the routes from Pan Am Corp.;    The plan, submitted to thecourt earlier this month when the airline filed for bankruptcy protection,calls for Pan Am to sell its five U.S.-to-London routes and certain otherassets to United for $400 million. Chicago-based UAL Corp., United's parent,also will provide Pan Am with $50 million in loans to help the strugglingcarrier.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  UNITED GETS OK TO BUY PAN AM'S LONDON ROUTES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Now the only major hurdle United faces is getting the British government tochange its law prohibiting Pan Am from transferring to another airline itsU.S. routes to Heathrow Airport.;    United overcame a major stumbling blocktoward that end this week when Britain's Civil Aviation Authority recommendedthat the British government change its 13-year-old rule banning new airlinesfrom flying into and out of Heathrow.;    The aviation authority said &quot;littlepurpose would be served&quot; in barring a transfer of Pan Am's landing and takeoffrights to United.;    The proposed transfer of the routes is opposed byBritish airlines because they fear the competition United is likely to givethem in Europe.;    &quot;The fact that the Civil Aviation Authority is not opposedto the transfer bodes very well for United,&quot; said Stephen Dexter of KemperFinancial Services.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Chicago Tribune  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Chicago  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910126  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><P